# Add tests for every implementation

Whenever you add or change behavior in this project, **add or update unit tests** in the same work session — do not leave new logic untested.

## Required workflow

1. **Implement** the feature.
2. **Extract testable logic** into `lib/` when possible (keep `app.js` and Netlify functions thin).
3. **Add tests** under `tests/` using Node's built-in test runner (`node:test` + `node:assert/strict`).
4. **Register new test files** in `scripts/run-tests.mjs`.
5. **Run** `./scripts/test.sh` (or `.\scripts\test.ps1`) and ensure **all tests pass** before committing.

## What must be tested

- Business rules (pricing, delivery fees, checkout validation)
- Payment flow logic (PIX payload, Mercado Pago mapping, payment status)
- Notification/message builders
- API client helpers (use injectable `fetch` mocks)
- Pure functions and edge cases (empty input, invalid data, failure paths)

## What to avoid testing

- Trivial one-liners with no logic
- Full browser DOM rendering (extract logic instead)
- External APIs for real (mock `fetch` in tests)

## Test file conventions

- Name files `tests/<area>.test.js`
- Group with `describe()` blocks by module or feature
- One clear assertion focus per `it()` when practical
- Mirror the structure of `lib/` (e.g. `lib/mercadopago.js` → `tests/mercadopago.test.js`)

## When modifying existing behavior

- Update affected tests — do not only add new ones if old tests would break or become wrong.
- If a bug fix has no test reproducing the bug, add one.

## Definition of done

A feature is **not done** until:

- [ ] New/changed logic has unit tests
- [ ] `scripts/run-tests.mjs` includes any new test files
- [ ] All tests pass locally
- [ ] Commit only after tests pass (see `run-tests-before-commit` rule)
